c practice. James Q. Davies and Ellen Lockhart gather work by leading scholars to explore a crucial sixty-year period, beginning with Charles Burney’s ambitious General History of Music, a four-volume study of music around the globe, and extending to the Great Exhibition of 1851, where musical instruments were assembled alongside the technologies of science and industry in the immense glass-encased collections of the Crystal Palace. Importantly, as the contributions show, both the power of science and the power of music relied on performance, spectacle, and experiment. Ultimately, this volume sets the stage for a new picture of modern disciplinarity, shining light on an era before the division of aural and visual knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMusic and sciencexHistoryy18th century. 0aMusic and sciencexHistoryy19th century. 0aMusiczEnglandzLondony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczEnglandzLondony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aScience - England - London - History - 19th century. 0aSciencezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aLondon.  ahistory of listening.  amusic.  anatural philosophy.  anineteenth-century.  apolitical economy.  ascience.  asound studies.  aspectacle.1 aDavies, James Q., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, James Q., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDickson, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolan, Emily I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHibberd, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Myles W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb